### KÂ*ND*IKÂ 4.

1. <span id="fr_387"></span>[1](#fn_387) By (the description of.md) the
Sthâlîpâka offered at the Anvash*t*akya ceremony the
Pi*nd*apit*ri*ya*gñ*a has been declared;

2\. This is a *S*râddha offered on the day of the new moon.

3. <span id="fr_388"></span>[3](#fn_388) Another (*S*râddha.md) is the
Anvâhârya.

4\. (It is performed) monthly.

5. <span id="fr_389"></span>[5](#fn_389.md) The Havis is prepared (by one
who has set up the sacred *S*rauta fires) in the Dakshi*n*âgni (i.e. in
that of the three fires which is situated towards the south).

6\. And from the same (fire the fire is taken which)

<span id="page_112">p. 112</span>

is carried forward (in order to be used at the ceremonies).

7\. In the domestic fire (the Havis is prepared) by one who has not set
up the (*S*rauta) fires.

8\. One pit (only is made);

9. <span id="fr_390"></span>[9](#fn_390.md) To the south of it the fire has
its place.

10. <span id="fr_391"></span>[10](#fn_391.md) Here the laying down of the
fire-brand is omitted,

11. <span id="fr_392"></span>[11](#fn_392) And (the spreading out of.md)
the layer (of grass),

12. <span id="fr_393"></span>[12](#fn_393.md) And the anointing (of the
bunches of Darbha grass), and the anointing (of the Fathers),

13. <span id="fr_394"></span>[13](#fn_394) And the (offering of.md)
perfume,

14. <span id="fr_395"></span>[14](#fn_395.md) And the ceremony of
deprecation.

15. <span id="fr_396"></span>[15](#fn_396) (The ceremony performed with.md)
the vessel of water forms the conclusion (of the Pi*nd*apit*ri*ya*gñ*a).

16. <span id="fr_397"></span>[16](#fn_397.md) He should, however, put down
one garment (for the Fathers in common).

17. <span id="fr_398"></span>[17](#fn_398.md) On the eighth day after the
full moon of Mâgha a Sthâlîpâka (is prepared).

18\. He should sacrifice of that (Sthâlîpâka).

19\. 'To the Ash*t*akâ Svâhâ!'—with (these words) he sacrifices.

20. <span id="fr_399"></span>[20](#fn_399.md) The rest (should be
performed) according to the Sthâlîpâka rite.

21. <span id="fr_400"></span>[21](#fn_400.md) Vegetables (are taken instead
of meat) as ingredient to the Anvâhârya(-rice).

22\. At animal sacrifices offered to the Fathers let—

<span id="page_113">p. 113</span>

him sacrifice the omentum with (the verse), 'Carry the omentum, O
*G*âtavedas, to the Fathers' (MB. II, 3, 16);

23\. At (such sacrifices) offered to the gods, with (the verse),
'*G*âtavedas, go to the gods with the omentum' (ibid. 17).

24\. If no (god to whom the sacrifice should be offered, and no Mantra
with which the oblation should be made) is known, he sacrifices,
assigning (his offering to the personified rite which he is performing),
thus as (for instance), 'To the Ash*t*akâ Svâhâ!'

25. <span id="fr_401"></span>[25](#fn_401.md) The rest (should be
performed) according to the Sthâlîpâka rite.

26. <span id="fr_402"></span>[26](#fn_402.md) If a debt turns up (which he
cannot pay), he should sacrifice with the middle leaf of Golakas, with
(the verse), 'The debt which' (MB. II, 3, 18).

27\. Now (follows) the putting into motion of the plough.

28\. Under an auspicious Nakshatra he should cook a mess of sacrificial
food and should sacrifice to the following deities, namely, to Indra, to
the Maruts, to Par*g*anya, to A*s*ani, to Bhaga.

29. <span id="fr_403"></span>[29](#fn_403) And he should offer (Â*g*ya.md)
to Sîtâ, Â*s*â, Ara*d*â, Anaghâ.

30\. The same deities (receive offerings) at the

<span id="page_114">p. 114</span>

furrow-sacrifice, at the thrashing-floor-sacrifice, at the sowing, at
the reaping of the crop, and at the putting of the crop into the barn.

31\. And at mole hills he should sacrifice to the king of moles.

32. <span id="fr_404"></span>[32](#fn_404.md) To Indrâ*n*î a Sthâlîpâka (is
prepared).

33\. Of that he should make an offering with (the verse), 'The
Ekâsh*t*akâ, performing austerities' (MB. II, 3, 19).

34\. The rest (should be performed) according to the Sthâlîpâka ritual.
The rest according to the Sthâlîpâka ritual.

